Good afternoon, Darrouzett Longhorns!

The Governor issued another Executive Order today that schools are to remain closed to campus-based education until May 4th. We will continue to provide remote instruction for our students until you return to the building on Monday, May 4th. We will continue to communicate with you daily. We are a community of learners and we are here to support you. Thank you for your willingness to learn with us during this time. Please use your distancing practices and stay healthy.

Good afternoon, The Darrouzett Longhorn Athletic Banquet scheduled for 6:00 p.m. on Monday, May 20th, is canceled due to the ongoing threat of severe weather and tornadoes. We will host an Athletic Awards Ceremony in the DISD Auditorium on Friday, May 24th, at 9:00 a.m. before our End of the Year Awards Assembly at 10:00 a.m. Please plan to join us for both celebrations. Go Longhorns!

post_text:
DISD is working hard to get ready for 2018-2019! There will be a couple of changes this year.
The Humphrey family has moved on to a school closer to family. We will miss them very much and Thank Mr. Humphrey for all of his hard work to improve and maintain Darrouzett school.
Mr. Ferguson will be the acting superintendent for a while‚Ä¶so please be patient as we make this transition. We‚Äôve moved a few people around, will welcome some new faces (along with welcoming back a familiar face :-) ) We want to remind you to register your students. Applications for substitutes for teaching, cafeteria and bus drivers are always welcome. Drop by and visit with Mr. Ferguson.
We thank you all for your continued support and interest in our school.
Donavan Ferguson

The Humphrey family has moved on to a school closer to family. We will miss them very much and Thank Mr. Humphrey for all of his hard work to improve and maintain Darrouzett school.
Mr. Ferguson will be the acting superintendent for a while‚Ä¶so please be patient as we make this transition. We‚Äôve moved a few people around, will welcome some new faces (along with welcoming back a familiar face :-) ) We want to remind you to register your students. Applications for substitutes for teaching, cafeteria and bus drivers are always welcome. Drop by and visit with Mr. Ferguson.
We thank you all for your continued support and interest in our school.
Donavan Ferguson

post_text:
We are EXTREMELY pleased to announce that Darrouzett ISD will be offering Industry-Based Certifications in the following areas for the 2018-2019 school year:

AWS Welding
Microsoft Office Expert- Word/Excel
QuickBooks

We are also starting up our new Culinary Arts program next year, which will be offered as an high school elective along with Industrial Arts, Theater and Yearbook.

It is our goal that every student who graduates from DISD will do so with either Dual-Credit College credit or an industry-based certificate. Alongside our 1:1 handheld technology program for students in grades 3-12, we feel these offerings will continue to strengthen our students chances for success upon graduation. #exceedingexpectations

post_text: The tragedy at Santa Fe High School today reminds us all of the importance of safety and security in schools. We want to assure our families that our district has an updated emergency operations plan in place. The members of our staff have been trained on the specifics of this plan, and we conduct periodic drills to ensure that everyone knows their role during a crisis. Our district also has specific protocols for entry to our school, and we appreciate the understanding of our parents as we enforce these protocols for the safety of our children. The safety of our students remains our highest priority. Our prayers go out to the students, staff and families affected by this tragedy.

shared_text:
Ken King
April 25, 2018 at 10:00 AM ¬∑

Our public schools have been a top priority of mine, even before I was elected to the Texas House in 2012. I have served on the House Public Education Committee since 2013, and currently am one of three House members on the School Finance Commission. This commission is studying school finance issues and working to find a solution, whether that involves reforming the current system or creating a new one. I want to give everyone in House District 88 the opportunity to share ideas, so I will be visiting every school board in the district before school starts in the fall. Our office will be reaching out to each school to schedule a visit. These meetings will be open to the public, and we will do our best to provide notice of dates and times. We have over 50 districts to visit, so we are asking some districts to combine with neighboring districts and hold a joint meeting when possible. We look forward to identifying solutions to better the future of our public schools during these visits.

Darrouzett ISD is currently taking applications for the upcoming 2018-2019 school year for all grade levels.

DISD is seeking motivated families who value a well-rounded educational experience and seek to take advantage of our all-day pre-kindergarten, low class sizes, free transportation for transfer students and friendly, small town environment.

Transfers will be granted based on academics, attendance, and discipline.

Transfer packets may be picked up at the front office or you can find them on our school website located at www.darrouzettisd.net.

post_text:
Results from the past week: Congratulations to Marcos Reyes on qualifying for the 1A Regional Track meet in Levelland on April 28th. On Monday, DISD competed in the Area Track Meet held in White Deer. Marcos won the 800m Run and finished second in the 1600m Run, advancing to regionals in both events. Dallas Bentley finished 5th in the Discus and Maddie Twilliger finished 6th in the 400m Dash.

Our academic team also competed this past weekend, with 15 students participating in the 1A Regional UIL Meet held in Levelland. DISD competed well, highlighted by Maddie Twilliger's 5th place finish in Ready Writing. Congratulations to all of our Longhorns on a great spring! Keep it going! #exceedingexpectations

post_text: VERY PROUD OF OUR LONGHORNS!!! Results are in from the HS District UIL Competition yesterday at Clarendon College! We had an outstanding meet last year, but this one was even better! Out of 27 students in our high school, 26 competed at the academic meet (96% participation rate). Darrouzett ended up with 3 team championships, 2 individual champions and a grand total of 15 students advancing to Regionals (56% of our total high school)!!! Despite being the smallest school in our district, Darrouzett finished 3rd overall. Congratulations to their coaches, Tracy Meier and Joyce Coppock, on great work this year. Way to go Longhorns and best of luck in Levelland! #exceedingexpectations
